    <node id="Nominal Pipe Size">
      <data key="d0">Nominal Pipe Size</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Nominal Pipe Size is a concept related to the dimensions of pipes.&lt;SEP&gt;Nominal Pipe Size is a standardized measurement for pipe dimensions.&lt;SEP&gt;Nominal Pipe Size (NPS) is a standard way to specify the size of pipes.&lt;SEP&gt;Nominal Pipe Size refers to the standardized size designation for pipes and corresponding flanges.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-29a21b64670fd3044048fc8ebefbb64a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-254e0b50334d5302f82bd70beda43312&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-55a057d80d0d30bec149f947f43931d5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Hub Diameter">
      <data key="d0">Hub Diameter</data>
      <data key="d1">concept</data>
      <data key="d2">Hub diameter is a dimension measured in Table 16 for various flange sizes.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter measures the diameter of the hub in the flange.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter is a critical dimension for flanges, especially when considering tapered designs.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter refers to the diameter of the hub portion of a flange.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter is a dimension measured across the hub of a flange.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter is a measurement related to the size of the hub.&lt;SEP&gt;Hub Diameter is a measurement related to the size of the hub in a flange.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edfa2a8d33668f4d57dbfceea1fab17e&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65bb92edfd06205fa901097f136f3ce0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-31bc32875a6306edfc4741462637a4e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3a41e880ec9f7ddef8b2a387e71dbd6a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c860be0c3f5ab97837a33d0776f228db&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-0df2a48018c5815fcbc69ee77e5e9629</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Minimum Corner Bore">
      <data key="d0">Minimum Corner Bore</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Minimum Corner Bore is the smallest diameter measurement at the corner of the flange bore.&lt;SEP&gt;Minimum Corner Bore is a measurement related to the smallest bore at the corner of a flange.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65bb92edfd06205fa901097f136f3ce0</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Beginning of Chamfer Length">
      <data key="d0">Beginning of Chamfer Length</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Beginning of Chamfer Length is the length of the chamfer at the beginning of the threaded portion of the flange.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Threaded Bore Radius">
      <data key="d0">Threaded Bore Radius</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Threaded Bore Radius is the radius of the bore where the threads are located.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Minimum Counterbore">
      <data key="d0">Minimum Counterbore</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Minimum Counterbore is the minimum depth of the counterbore in the flange.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Thickness">
      <data key="d0">Thickness</data>
      <data key="d1">measurement</data>
      <data key="d2">Thickness is the measure of how thick the flange is.&lt;SEP&gt;Thickness is a measurement related to the thickness of the material.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-edfa2a8d33668f4d57dbfceea1fab17e</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Slip-On Flange">
      <data key="d0">Slip-On Flange</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Slip-On Flange is a type of flange attached to a pipe by slipping it over the end of the pipe and welding.&lt;SEP&gt;Slip-On Flange is a type of flange that is slipped over a pipe and then welded in place.&lt;SEP&gt;Slip-On Flange is a type of flange that is slipped onto the pipe and held in place by welding.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-31bc32875a6306edfc4741462637a4e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1991062d5c6aa490277d1b30a0762cee</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="ASME">
      <data key="d0">ASME</data>
      <data key="d1">organization</data>
      <data key="d2">ASME (American Society of Mechanical Engineers) is an organization that develops and publishes standards for various industries, including pressure vessel and pipeline systems. ASME is known for publishing standards such as ASME B16.5-2013, which covers flanges,法兰, and法兰面. ASME International is responsible for publishing and maintaining these standard documents, and it also owns the copyright and serves as the governing body for the standard documents. Additionally, ASME licenses certain certifications, though the specific certification mentioned (HS) is not detailed in the provided descriptions.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-eea4d2a4c70f14b7096c0e2adae1b686&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-98e6bd64e65f31d06ced3b3e90f47312&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-fbc7ddba32bbe5c4b27763a8da4efefb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-545818ef44ac301232f6e8003ced593b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-da0eb2037f412344871720430fa6cf02&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a5a59c9e110a47eb7eef51fb2fb81c5a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-faa44ee0ab9a603579ea4693825fe3ea&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2ee06a2df0130f4a0dc8ec87fdc1d0c4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-516a0d0d88a2b8acdc1bf3b705deb645&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-47bb2fa75b3e7cd5e145f1d353440450</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Lapped Joint Flange">
      <data key="d0">Lapped Joint Flange</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Lapped Joint Flange is a type of flange that is furnished with flat faces and is used with lap joints.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped Joint Flange is a type of flange where the flange is lapped over the pipe and held in place by bolts.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-5b5b0e2acae20a65c1c3b15054804a3f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-770491ae4c5f3e5340337d3d781061d5</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Group 1.14 Materials">
      <data key="d0">Group 1.14 Materials</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Group 1.14 Materials refers to specific materials with certain pressure-temperature ratings.&lt;SEP&gt;Group 1.14 Materials are another set of materials with specific pressure–temperature ratings.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c8f0d95695be35b4525eefd339a3b500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-47bb2fa75b3e7cd5e145f1d353440450</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Working Pressures by Classes, bar">
      <data key="d0">Working Pressures by Classes, bar</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Working Pressures by Classes, bar categorizes the pressure ratings for different temperature classes.&lt;SEP&gt;Working pressures by classes in bar are listed for various temperatures and material groups.&lt;SEP&gt;Working pressures by classes are listed in bar units for different temperature ranges.&lt;SEP&gt;Working Pressures by Classes, bar is a concept referring to the pressure ratings at different temperature classes.&lt;SEP&gt;Working Pressures by Classes, bar is a table that lists the maximum allowable working pressures for different temperature classes.&lt;SEP&gt;Working Pressures by Classes, bar categorizes the pressure ratings in the table.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c8f0d95695be35b4525eefd339a3b500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-656b6734cce47f14e81f0e8c31c77d35&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f85b34e2860017c4a2a3af023715b984&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b4364e68825dbe4e5d2b1711332b9ba&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e5cd3565858655527cd4c1e3bec3a75&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b80a9d659f34e9872ec7554628906bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f64edd2488182d1fe2576b6fcef9b20&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c21da8c1a6a154a2c6aadf64e368d44b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Temp., °C">
      <data key="d0">Temp., °C</data>
      <data key="d1">category</data>
      <data key="d2">Temp., °C indicates the temperature in degrees Celsius for which the pressure ratings are given.&lt;SEP&gt;Temperature ranges are listed in degrees Celsius for different working pressure classes.&lt;SEP&gt;Temp., °C is a concept referring to temperature in degrees Celsius.&lt;SEP&gt;Temp., °C categorizes the temperature classes for which pressure ratings are provided.&lt;SEP&gt;Temp., °C indicates the temperature range for the pressure ratings.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c8f0d95695be35b4525eefd339a3b500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f85b34e2860017c4a2a3af023715b984&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-5e5cd3565858655527cd4c1e3bec3a75&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b80a9d659f34e9872ec7554628906bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f64edd2488182d1fe2576b6fcef9b20&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c21da8c1a6a154a2c6aadf64e368d44b</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255080</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="-29 to 38">
      <data key="d0">-29 to 38</data>
      <data key="d1">temperaturerange</data>
      <data key="d2">-29 to 38°C is the temperature range for which certain pressure ratings are applicable.&lt;SEP&gt;-29 to 38°C is a temperature range for working pressure classes.&lt;SEP&gt;-29 to 38°C is a temperature range listed in the table.&lt;SEP&gt;-29 to 38 is a temperature range in degrees Celsius.&lt;SEP&gt;-29 to 38°C is the temperature range for which certain pressure ratings are provided.&lt;SEP&gt;-29 to 38°C is the temperature range for the first class of working pressures.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-c8f0d95695be35b4525eefd339a3b500&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f85b34e2860017c4a2a3af023715b984&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-913ab8bf8d15091a1c354835260c5873&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-2b80a9d659f34e9872ec7554628906bb&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3f64edd2488182d1fe2576b6fcef9b20&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-c21da8c1a6a154a2c6aadf64e368d44b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-1b4364e68825dbe4e5d2b1711332b9ba</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
