    <node id="Lapped Flange">
      <data key="d0">Lapped Flange</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Lapped flange is a type of flange described in Table 16, where the&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped Flange is a type of flange where the flange face is lapped against the pipe face.&lt;SEP&gt;Lapped Flange is a type of flange where the mating surfaces are joined by lapping.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-32c51ff12b3c72377950aac97432147f&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-31bc32875a6306edfc4741462637a4e5&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-3a41e880ec9f7ddef8b2a387e71dbd6a</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255082</data>
      <data key="d6" />
    </node>
    <node id="Blind Flanges">
      <data key="d0">Blind Flanges</data>
      <data key="d1">artifact</data>
      <data key="d2">Blind flanges are flat, round plates used to close off the end of a pipe or pipe fitting. These components are typically thick and are covered by standards such as ASME B16.5-2013, which specifies various rating classes and sizes. Blind flanges can be made with or without hubs, depending on the manufacturer's specifications or the requirements outlined in the standard. They are commonly used in industrial applications where a tight seal is necessary, and they serve as a means to isolate sections of piping systems for maintenance or testing purposes.</data>
      <data key="d3">chunk-7ea1b2e76d1f000d5569b9486b9e5ac4&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-dd9487a2f3662945039d8bc799ee92b9&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-f28c7d4bdd4e434720bb2e0817acb7da&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a5a59c9e110a47eb7eef51fb2fb81c5a&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-65bb92edfd06205fa901097f136f3ce0&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-7040bbb99f12a42660ed8b6b948c1e9b&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-a560aa3224b393530e878cd8da41ea17&lt;SEP&gt;chunk-6b3d3983136bf26d485546eb760e1ee8</data>
      <data key="d4">unknown_source</data>
      <data key="d5">1776255082</data>
